"Yes, sir. They should be on their way now; we gave them time to get rations from the mess." At exactly 5:00, the Exodus company was gathered at the vehicle park. Shaw climbed onto a crate and began to speak.
"We are deploying to FOB I-131, eighty kilometers from Ianlos. We must support the ongoing siege and the planned attack on Ianlos to quell the insurgency. From there, we will have an advanced position and a base at the foot of the mountains," explained Shaw. "Gather your units and board the vehicles."
The company dispersed, everyone joining their unit, and the sergeants had them board the tanks. Cohren climbed into one of the armored vehicles, at the front of the convoy, and joined Nemic, Craith, and two new recruits. Cohren remembered their arrival a few days earlier, but he didn't know much about them. Sitting on the side, legs dangling, he adjusted his pack and his radio equipment, which was connected to his earpiece and throat mic.
"Hey Cohren, does Harris still have Snowball?" Nemic asked as they settled in.
"You mean the chicken he stole?" Cohren remembered the morning they had stolen it from a farm. "Yes, I'm sure."
Cohren glanced toward one of the tanks and spotted Harris with his unit. From the back of his pack, he could just make out the movement of a small chicken wiggling its head to observe the surroundings.
"Yeah, he still has it," Cohren replied as the tank turret opened with a clank to let his commander pass through.
"All tanks are moving," declared the commander calmly, but clearly through his helmet. The engines of a platoon of tanks and Strykers roared as they began to move forward. The Kronos on which Cohren was situated jolted when its brakes were released and it started moving to get into formation. The tanks spread out in a V formation to cross the plains of Itania. The winter storms had frozen the swamps and forests, but the mud was still there.
After about an hour, one of the new recruits, named Orson in Cohren's memory, spoke up. "Lieutenant, you've been here since the beginning of the war, right?"
"Yeah, Operation Firestorm," Cohren replied. "We thought we'd wrap it up in a few weeks, but... we underestimated them."
"Underestimating is a weak word," said Nemic joining the conversation. "They had more weapons and men than we anticipated. They managed to down the UFS Revenant in the first two weeks, and Erebus last month. Shit, we should see it from the road we're on."
"Well, I'll hold strong for the Federation," said Orson a bit provocatively. "I won't let these terrorists scare me."
"You say that now, but from experience, I know that young recruits like you, who are 18 years old, take cover as soon as they hear gunfire," declared Craith.
"I think we'll find out soon," said Corhen laughing. Orson did not continue the conversation.
"Exodus XO, Exodus CO," crackled Cohren's radio. "We are detecting thermal signatures approximately 300 meters away, 20 degrees to the right."
Cohren climbed to the top of the tank and put on his optical goggles. Activating thermal vision, he was able to see thermal signatures in the distance.
"Yep, I see them," Cohren replied through his throat mic.
"Enemies?" asked the other recruit, Natayla.
"Impossible to say," Cohren declared. He activated his mic and said, "Company Exodus, don't fire unless they fire at you, let's get them out."
As they approached, the small thermal signatures went from blurry spots to more distinct shapes. As they got closer, one of them ran toward something, grabbed it, and then rushed again toward the small ridge where they were. The silhouettes took their shooting positions.
"We have contacts," Shaw shouted into the radio, as orange tracers were fired from the ridge. The bullets ricocheted off the sides of the tanks, while soldiers jumped from vehicles to take cover behind them. An anti-tank missile whistled past and crashed to the ground behind the formation, exploding and sending debris onto one of the vehicles. Another missile struck the side of a Stryker, an APS-Cerberus, and exploded. Its crew crawled out and dove for cover as the ammunition caught fire.
"Iron 1-2 and &-", 25 degrees to the right, 275 meters. "Fire," shouted the tank platoon commander over the radio. Iron 1-2 and 1-3 opened fire, their shells flew toward the ridge and exploded, sending mud and stones into the air.
"Send the Senti," cried Knoxx, who was observing the ridge through his binoculars. The back of one of the Cerberus units opened and a disarmed soldier wearing a special helmet emerged. He barked orders into a square microphone and two Senti, or Sentinels by their official name, rushed outside. Their thin metallic arms and legs swung forward as they sprinted. They were armed, but their weapons were attached to their backs.
"Do we kill them or capture them?" Craith asked as they watched them.
"It seems we capture them," Cohren said as the two Sentinels disappeared into a cloud of ash and smoke. Shouts and gunfire echoed from the ridge, but quickly ceased. A moment later, the two Sentinels returned, dragging someone behind them, whose boots dragged along the ground. Once safe with the platoon, they threw the individual to the ground. He groaned in pain as he collapsed into the mud and snow.
Shaw walked toward the individual, who was beginning to rise. He turned toward one of the Sentinels. "How many?"
"Three dead, sir," the Sentinel replied. "The others fled on foot."
Shaw nodded and turned toward Cohren and Craith, who were standing beside him. "Both of you, would you kindly get rid of this man?"
